---
title: "Doing cool things with the Discrete Cosine Transform in tidynorm"
description: "DCT coefficients are really useful!"
date: 2025-06-17
format: html
fig-width: 6
fig-asp: 0.618
out-width: 70%
editor: visual
---

[Yesterday](../2025-06-16_introducing-tidynorm/) I posted about the normalization functions in the `{tidynorm}` R package.
In order to implement formant track normalization, I had to also put together code for working with the Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT), which in and of itself can be handy to work with.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
library(tidynorm)
library(tidyverse)
library(geomtextpath)
library(gt)

source(here::here("_defaults.R"))
```
:::


## The DCT

[I've posted about the DCT before](../../../2024/07/2024-07-19_dct-r/), but to put it briefly, the DCT tries to re-describe an input signal in terms of weighted and summed cosine functions.
The DCT basis looks like this:


::: {.cell layout-align="center" renderings='["light","dark"]'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="plotting code"}
dct_mat <- dct_basis(100, k = 5)

as_tibble(
  dct_mat, 
  .name_repair = "unique"
) |> 
  mutate(
    x = row_number()
  ) |> 
  pivot_longer(
    starts_with("...")
  ) |> 
  ggplot(
    aes(x, value, color = name)
  ) +
    geom_line(
      linewidth = 1
    ) +
  guides(color = "none") +
  labs(y = NULL) +
  theme_no_x()->p

p
p+theme_dark()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-2-1.png){fig-align='center' width=60%}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-2-2.png){fig-align='center' width=60%}
:::
:::


If we grab one vowel's formant track and fit a linear model using these functions as predictors, the coefficients will equal the DCT coefficients.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
speaker_tracks |> 
  filter(
    speaker == "s01",
    plt_vclass == "ay"
  ) |> 
  filter(id == first(id)) ->
  one_ay
```
:::



::: {.cell layout-align="center" renderings='["light","dark"]'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="plotting code"}
one_ay |> 
  ggplot(
    aes(t, F1)
  )+
  geom_point(color = ptol_red, size = 2)->
  p

p
p + theme_dark()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-4-1.png){fig-align='center' width=50%}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-4-2.png){fig-align='center' width=50%}
:::
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# 5 dct coefficients
# for a formant track with
# 20 measurement points
dct_mat <- dct_basis(20, k = 5)

dct_mod <- lm(one_ay$F1 ~ dct_mat - 1)

dct_direct <- tidynorm::dct(one_ay$F1)[1:5]

cbind(
  coef(dct_mod),
  dct_direct
)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
                      dct_direct
dct_mat1 602.3486557 602.3486557
dct_mat2  97.7676452  97.7676452
dct_mat3  -0.4687751  -0.4687751
dct_mat4  -7.1061819  -7.1061819
dct_mat5 -19.4956181 -19.4956181
```


:::
:::


## Using the DCT to Smooth

A cool thing about the DCT is that it can be used to smooth formant tracks.
We can see that smoothing effect if we plot the inverse DCT of the coefficients we just got.


::: {.cell layout-align="center" renderings='["light","dark"]'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="plotting code"}
one_ay |> 
  mutate(
    F1_s = idct(
      dct_direct, n = n()
      )
  ) |> 
  ggplot(
    aes(
      t
    )
  ) +
  geom_point(
    aes(y = F1, color = "original")
  ) +
  geom_line(
    aes(y = F1_s, color = "dct smooth"),
    linewidth = 1
  )+
  labs(
    color = NULL
  ) -> p

p
p + theme_dark()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-2.png){fig-align='center' width=70%}
:::
:::


In `tidynorm()` we can get these smoothed formant tracks with `reframe_with_dct_smooth()`.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# grabbing a sample of
# a few vowel tracks
set.seed(2025-06)
speaker_tracks |> 
  filter(
    speaker == "s01",
    plt_vclass == "ay0"
  ) |> 
  filter(
    id %in% sample(unique(id), 5)
  ) ->
  ay_tracks

# smoothing happens here
ay_tracks |> 
  reframe_with_dct_smooth(
    F1:F3,
    .token_id_col = id,
    .time_col = t
  ) ->
  ay_smooths
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="plotting code"}
ay_tracks |> 
  ggplot(
    aes(F2, F1)
  ) +
  geom_path(
    aes(color = factor(id)),
    arrow = arrow(
      type = "closed",
      angle = 25,
      length = unit(0.5, "cm")
    ),
    linewidth = 1
  ) +
  guides(
    color = "none"
  ) +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  scale_x_reverse() ->
  track_p

track_p %+% ay_smooths ->
  smooth_p
```
:::


::: {layout-ncol="2"}

::: {.cell renderings='["light","dark"]'}
